<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>DT-466E and 530E Diesel Engine Service (1995 through 1999) - SECTION 7: VIBRATION DAMPER, CRANKSHAFT, MAIN
        BEARINGS, FLYWHEEL AND CRANKCASE - REAR OIL SEAL AND WEAR SLEEVE - REAR OIL SEAL AND CARRIER INSTALLATION
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="install" graphiccount="9">
        <title>REAR OIL SEAL AND CARRIER INSTALLATION</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Flywheel Housing Removed</title>
            <para>Install rear oil seal carrier as follows:</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Attach rear oil seal guide
                    <emph type="bold">ZTSE4374b</emph>
                    to crankshaft flange and secure by tightening the two (2) mounting bolts (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600716">7.16</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Place a new gasket into rear oil seal carrier. Install rear oil seal carrier to
                    crankcase and loosely secure with oil seal carrier mounting bolts (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600717">7.17</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the driver guide tool
                    <emph type="bold">ZTSE4374b</emph>
                    over the crankshaft (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600718">7.18</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
                <figure id="ef1600716" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg5183" filename="../figeg5/eg5183.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.16 Installing Carrier Guide</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1600717" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg6908" filename="../figeg6/eg6908.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.17 Installing Gasket Onto Carrier</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">1. Oil Seal Carrier Gasket</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1600718" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg5189" filename="../figeg5/eg5189.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.18 Installing Driver Guide Tool</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Tighten driver nut to center the oil seal carrier to the crankcase (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure</emph>
                    <emph type="bold">
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600719">7.19</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ). Finger-tighten the carrier and remove the driver guide tool.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Rotate/twist the carrier, if necessary, to align carrier with crankcase rails. Use
                    straight edge
                    <emph type="bold">OEM1293</emph>
                    to verify (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600720">7.20</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">When the rear oil seal carrier is level, tighten the mounting bolts to the special
                    torque value (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600721">7.21</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
                <figure id="ef1600719" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg5190" filename="../figeg5/eg5190.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.19 Centering Oil Seal Carrier</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1600720" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg5275" filename="../figeg5/eg5275.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.20 Aligning Oil Seal Carrier</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1600721" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg5186" filename="../figeg5/eg5186.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.21 Securing Oil Seal Carrier</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>INSTALL THE REAR OIL SEAL AND WEAR SLEEVE AS A UNIT. DO NOT REMOVE THE SEAL FROM THE WEAR
                            SLEEVE PRIOR TO INSTALLATION.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install a new rear oil seal and crankshaft wear sleeve assembly using installer tool
                    <emph type="bold">ZTSE4374b</emph>
                    as follows:
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Clean crankshaft flange and seal carrier bore thoroughly. Remove any debris.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Attach rear oil seal/wear sleeve guide to crankshaft flange and secure with two (2)
                        mounting screws (
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600722">7.22</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        ).
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Coat inner I.D. of wear sleeve and O.D. of oil seal with Aviation Permatex #3 (
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600723">7.23</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        ).
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Position oil seal and wear sleeve over crankshaft.</para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>Proper use of installer tool will assure that seal and wear sleeve are pressed onto
                                the crankshaft flange to the proper depth.
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Assemble rear oil seal/wear sleeve installer tool onto crankshaft. Using a wrench,
                        turn forcing nut on installer tool until seal and sleeve are seated in the bore (
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600724">7.24</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        ).
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove oil seal/wear sleeve installation tool.</para>
                    <figure id="ef1600722" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg5174" filename="../figeg5/eg5174.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 7.22 Attach Guide To Crankshaft</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef1600723" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg5178" filename="../figeg5/eg5178.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 7.23 Preparing Oil Seal/ Wear Sleeve</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef1600724" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg5190" filename="../figeg5/eg5190.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 7.24 Installing Oil Seal/ Wear Sleeve</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
